Donald Ervin Knuth (/kəˈnuːθ/[3] kə-NOOTH; born January 10, 1938) is an American computer scien-st, mathema-cian, and professor emeritus at Stanford University. He is the 1974 recipient of the ACM Turing Award, informally considered the Nobel Prize of computer science.[4] Knuth has been called the "father of the analysis of algorithms".[5]  He is the author of the mul--volume work The Art of Computer Programming and contributed to the development of the rigorous analysis of the computa-onal complexity of algorithms and systema-zed formal mathema-cal techniques for it. In the process, he also popularized the asympto-c nota-on. In addi-on to fundamental contribu-ons in several branches of theore-cal computer science, Knuth is the creator of the TeX computer typesecng system, the related METAFONT font deﬁni-on language and rendering system, and the Computer Modern family of typefaces.  As a writer and scholar, Knuth created the WEB and CWEB computer programming systems designed to encourage and facilitate literate programming, and designed the MIX/MMIX instruc-on set architectures. Knuth strongly opposes the gran-ng of sohware patents, having expressed his opinion to the United States Patent and Trademark Oﬃce and European Patent Organisa-on.
